  hydrogen gas due to electrolysis.  This is especially true for overcharged lead-acid
  cells, but not exclusive to that type.  Hydrogen is an extremely flammable gas (especially
  in the presence of free oxygen created by the same electrolysis process), odorless
  and colorless.  Such batteries pose an explosion threat even under normal operating
  conditions, and must be treated with respect.  The author has been a firsthand witness
  to a lead-acid battery explosion, where a spark created by the removal of a battery
  charger (small DC power supply) from an automotive battery ignited hydrogen gas
  within the battery case, blowing the top off the battery and splashing sulfuric
  acid everywhere.  This occurred in a high school automotive shop, no less.  If it
  were not for all the students nearby wearing safety glasses and buttoned-collar
  overalls, significant injury could have occurred.

