? 'Conversely, if a very light load (1 mA) were to be connected to the battery, our
  equation would tell us that the battery should provide power for 70,000 hours, or
  just under 8 years (70 amp-hours / 1 milliamp), but the odds are that much of the
  chemical energy in a real battery would have been drained due to other factors (evaporation
  of electrolyte, deterioration of electrodes, leakage current within battery) long
  before 8 years had elapsed.  Therefore, we must take the amp-hour relationship as
  being an ideal approximation of battery life, the amp-hour rating trusted only near
  the specified current or timespan given by the manufacturer.  Some manufacturers
  will provide amp-hour derating factors specifying reductions in total capacity at
  different levels of current and/or temperature.

  '
